<br>
Don't make me laugh.  Guns are easily available in every run down neighborhood from your local thug/gang.  To dispute the fact that guns are rampant throughout the US, and easily accessable to boot, is akin to denying that 1+1=2.  It really is that simple, and if you care to debate it I'm sure I can pull up some real scary official stats about it.  This is besides the fact that at least as of four years ago, you could buy hunting rifles at K-mart.  Sure, you can't buy one if your under 18, have a criminal record, etc--but then again who cares when your local gang will just break in, steal them, and resell them dirt cheap.  For gods sake, last time I visited my mom in Texas there was a sign outside a mini-mart that said &quot;no guns allowed inside&quot;.  ROFL, I even took a picture to show friends back home.  Very scary imho.  In Canada, I couldn't even tell you where they sell guns, let alone how to buy them. Since they aren't available pretty much anywhere, only organized crime has access to these weapons.<br>
<br>
Wasn't trying to &quot;insult&quot; the US, just make some comparisons.  Sorry if you interpreted fact as an insult to either your love of handguns or the US.  The fact is I've spent a third of my life living in the US, but I must admit some of their policies, specifically &quot;the right to bear arms&quot; are sometimes simply antiquated or plain stupid.<br>
<br>
<br>
